# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: slsa-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:slsa-framework/devsecops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The practice has a particular value in helping authenticate objects.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Comparative techniques, expert opinions and the results of scientific tests may also be used to these ends, but establishing provenance is essentially a matter of documentation.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Provenance is conceptually comparable to the legal term *chain of custody*.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] For museums and the art trade, in addition to helping establish the authorship and authenticity of an object, provenance has become increasingly important in helping establish the moral and legal validity of a chain of custody, given the increasing amount of looted art.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] These issues first became a major concern regarding works that had changed hands in Nazi-controlled areas in Europe before and during World War II.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Many museums began compiling pro-active registers of such works and their history.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Recently the same concerns have come to prominence for works of African art, often exported illegally, and antiquities from many parts of the world, but currently especially in Iraq, and then Syria.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In archaeology and paleontology, the derived term **provenience** is used with a related but very particular meaning, to refer to the location (in modern research, recorded precisely in three dimensions) where an artifact or other ancient item was found.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] *Provenance* covers an object's complete documented history.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] An artifact may thus have both a provenience and a provenance.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The provenance of works of fine art, antiques and antiquities is of great importance, especially to their owner.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] There are a number of reasons why painting provenance is important, which mostly also apply to other types of fine art.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] A good provenance increases the value of a painting, and establishing provenance may help confirm the date, artist and, especially for portraits, the subject of a painting.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] It may confirm whether a painting is genuinely of the period it seems to date from.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The provenance of paintings can help resolve ownership disputes.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] For example, provenance between 1933 and 1945 can determine whether a painting was looted by the Nazis.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Many galleries are putting a great deal of effort into researching the provenance of paintings in their collections for which there is no firm provenance during that period.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Documented evidence of provenance for an object can help to establish that it has not been altered and is not a forgery, a reproduction, stolen or looted art.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Provenance helps assign the work to a known artist, and a documented history can be of use in helping to prove ownership.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] An example of a detailed provenance is given in the Arnolfini portrait.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The quality of provenance of an important work of art can make a considerable difference to its selling price in the market.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] This is affected by the degree of certainty of the provenance, the status of past owners as collectors, and in many cases by the strength of evidence that an object has not been illegally excavated or exported from another country.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The provenance of a work of art may vary greatly in length, depending on context or the amount that is known, from a single name to an entry in a scholarly catalogue some thousands of words long.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] An expert certification can mean the difference between an object having no value and being worth a fortune.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Certifications themselves may be open to question.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Jacques van Meegeren forged the work of his father Han van Meegeren, who had forged the work of Vermeer.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Jacques sometimes produced a certificate with his forgeries, stating that a work was created by his father.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] John Drewe was able to pass off as genuine paintings, a large number of forgeries that would have easily been recognised as such by scientific examination.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] He established an impressive, but false provenance.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Because of this, galleries and dealers accepted the paintings as genuine.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] He created this false provenance by forging letters and other documents, including false entries in earlier exhibition catalogues.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Sometimes provenance can be as simple as a photograph of the item with its original owner.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Simple yet definitive documentation such as that can increase its value by an order of magnitude, but only if the owner was of high renown.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Many items that were sold at auction have gone far past their estimates because of a photograph showing that item with a famous person.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Some examples include antiques owned by politicians, musicians, artists, actors, etc.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In the context of discussions about the restitution of cultural objects in museum collections of colonial origin, the AfricaMuseum in Belgium started to publicly present information about such objects in its permanent exhibition in 2021.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The objective of provenance research is to produce a complete list of owners (together, where possible, with the supporting documentary proof) from when the painting was commissioned or in the artist's studio through to the present time.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In practice, there are likely to be gaps in the list and documents that are missing or lost.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The documented provenance should also list when the painting has been part of an exhibition and a bibliography of when it has been discussed, or illustrated in print.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Where the research is proceeding backwards, to discover the previous provenance of a painting whose current ownership and location are known, it is important to record the physical details of the painting – style, subject, signature, materials, dimensions, frame, etc.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The titles of paintings and the attribution to a particular artist may change over time.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The size of the work and its description can be used to identify earlier references to the painting.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The back of a painting can contain significant provenance information.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] There may be exhibition marks, dealer stamps, gallery labels and other indications of previous ownership.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In the BBC TV programme *Fake or Fortune?* the provenance of the painting *Bords de la Seine à Argenteuil* was investigated using a gallery sticker and shipping label on the back.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Early provenance can sometimes be indicated by a *cartellino*, a *trompe-l'œil* representation of an inscribed label, added to the front of a painting.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] However, these can be forged, or can fade or be painted over.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Auction records are an important resource to assist in researching the provenance of paintings.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] If a painting has been in private hands for an extended period and on display in a stately home, it may be recorded in an inventory – for example, the Lumley inventory.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The painting may also have been noticed by a visitor who subsequently wrote about it.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] It may have been mentioned in a will or a diary.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Where the painting has been bought from a dealer, or changed hands in a private transaction, there may be a bill of sale or sales receipt that provides evidence of provenance.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Where the artist is known, there may be a *catalogue raisonné* listing all the artist's known works and their location at the time of writing.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] A database of *catalogues raisonné* is available at the International Foundation for Art Research.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Historic photos of the painting may be discussed and illustrated in a more general work on the artist, period or genre.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Similarly, a photograph of a painting may show inscriptions (or a signature) that subsequently became lost as a result of overzealous restoration.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Conversely, a photograph may show that an inscription was not visible at an earlier date.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] One of the disputed aspects of the "Rice" portrait of Jane Austen concerns apparent inscriptions identifying artist and sitter.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Provenance – also known as **custodial history** – is a core concept within archival science and archival processing.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The term refers to the individuals, groups, or organizations that originally created or received the items in an accumulation of records, and to the items' subsequent chain of custody.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Conversely, records of different provenance should be preserved and documented separately.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In archival practice, proof of provenance is provided by the operation of control systems that document the history of records kept in archives, including details of amendments made to them.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The authority of an archival document or set of documents of which the provenance is uncertain, because of gaps in the recorded chain of custody, will be considered to be severely compromised.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The principles of archival provenance were developed in the 19th century by both French and Prussian archivists, and gained widespread acceptance on the basis of their formulation in the *Manual for the Arrangement and Description of Archives* by Dutch state archivists Samuel Muller, J.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Fruin, published in the Netherlands in 1898, often referred to as the "Dutch Manual".
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Seamus Ross has argued a case for adapting established principles and theories of archival provenance to the field of modern digital preservation and curation.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In the case of books, the study of provenance refers to the study of the ownership of individual copies of books.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] It is usually extended to include the study of the circumstances in which individual copies of books have changed ownership, and of evidence left in books that shows how readers interacted with them.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Provenance studies may shed light on the books themselves, providing evidence of the role particular titles have played in social, intellectual and literary history.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Such studies may also add to our knowledge of particular owners of books.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] For instance, looking at the books owned by a writer may help to show which works influenced him or her.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Many provenance studies are historically focused, and concentrated on books owned by writers, politicians and public figures.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The recent ownership of books is studied, however, as is evidence of how ordinary or anonymous readers have interacted with books.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Provenance can be studied both by examining the books themselves, for instance looking at inscriptions, marginalia, bookplates, book rhymes, and bindings, and by reference to external sources of information such as auction catalogues.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Provenance for pianos is authenticated before a piano is inducted into a museum, sold at an auction, or appraised for an estate or legal action, when it has extraordinary value in connection to a composer, performer, event or location that has become famous.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] For example, the piano that Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart used during the final 10 years of his life, is on display in the Mozarteum Museum in Salzburg, one of many historical pianos in museums around the world.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The 300,000th Steinway piano that was presented to President Franklin D.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Roosevelt by Theodore Steinway, on behalf of the Steinway family is on display in the White House.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] It is one of many pianos with a provenance that have extraordinary value because of art, sculpture or design incorporated into the cabinet.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] It has legs carved into golden eagles and figures painted on the body of the piano.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] For a piano, provenance can be established by starting with the authentication of the brand of manufacture and serial number, which will usually identify age.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Then bills of sale, tuning records, bills of lading, concert programs that identify a piano by serial number, letters, famous signatures inside or on the outside of a piano, statements under oath in a court of law and photographs can all help authenticate a piano's provenance.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Pianos can sell for millions of dollars, when the provenance is significant enough to increase its value well beyond what it would be worth as a musical instrument alone.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Piano provenance has emerged as a field of study with experts having college degrees in some specialty connected to the piano or to art combined with professional training and experience in the field.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Most experts belong to some form of association.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In the case of sculpture or art that are incorporated into the piano's cabinet, experts might be come from the field of art valuation and belong to an appraiser society such as the American Society of Appraisers or the International Society of Appraisers.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In transactions of old wine with the potential of improving with age, the issue of provenance has a large bearing on the assessment of the contents of a bottle, both in terms of quality and the risk of wine fraud.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] A documented history of wine cellar conditions is valuable in estimating the quality of an older vintage due to the fragile nature of wine.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Recent technology developments have aided collectors in assessing the temperature and humidity history of the wine which are two key components in establishing perfect provenance.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] For example, there are devices available that rest inside the wood case and can be read through the wood by waving a smartphone equipped with a simple app.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] These devices track the conditions the case has been exposed to for the duration of the battery life, which can be as long as 15 years, and sends a graph and high/low readings to the smartphone user.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] This takes the trust issue out of the hands of the owner and gives it to a third party for verification.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Ideally, in modern excavations, the provenience is recorded in three dimensions on a site grid with great precision, and may also be recorded on video to provide additional proof and context.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In older work, often undertaken by amateurs, only the general site or approximate area may be known, especially when an artifact was found outside a professional excavation and its specific position not recorded.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The term *provenience* appeared in the 1880s, about a century after *provenance*.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Outside of academic contexts, it has been used as a synonymous variant spelling of *provenance*, especially in American English.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Digital analytical methods have also been applied to the reconstruction of archaeological provenience.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] For example, a 2025 study used high-resolution three-dimensional surface comparison to identify ancient Egyptian artefacts produced from the same mould, contributing to the reassessment of their original context.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Any given antiquity may have both a provenience, where it was found, and a provenance, where it has been since it was found.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] A summary of the distinction is that "provenience is a fixed point, while provenance can be considered an itinerary that an object follows as it moves from hand to hand." Another metaphor is that provenience is an artifact's "birthplace", while provenance is its "résumé".
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Many artifacts originated as trade goods created in one region, but were used and finally deposited in another.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In this context, the *provenance* can occasionally be the detailed history of where an object has been since its creation, as in art history contexts – not just since its modern finding.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Evidence of provenance in the more general sense can be of importance in archaeology.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Fakes are not unknown, and finds are sometimes removed from the context in which they were found without documentation, reducing their value to science.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Even when apparently discovered *in situ*, archaeological finds are treated with caution.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The provenience of a find may not be properly represented by the context in which it was found, e.g. due to stratigraphic layers being disturbed by erosion, earthquakes, or ancient reconstruction or other disturbance at a site.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Artifacts can be moved through looting as well as trade, far from their place of origin and long before modern rediscovery.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Many source nations have passed legislation forbidding the domestic trade in cultural heritage.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Further research is often required to establish the true provenance and legal status of a find, and what the relationship is between the exact provenience and the overall provenance.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In paleontology and paleoanthropology, it is recognized that fossils can also move from their primary context and are sometimes found, apparently *in-situ*, in deposits to which they do not belong because they have been moved, for example, by the erosion of nearby but different outcrops.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] It is unclear how strictly paleontology maintains the *provenience* and *provenance* distinction.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] For example, a short glossary at a website, primarily aimed at young students, of the American Museum of Natural History treats the terms as synonymous, while scholarly paleontology works make frequent use of *provenience* in the same precise sense as used in archaeology and paleoanthropology.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] While exacting details of a find's provenience are primarily of use to scientific researchers, most natural history and archaeology museums also make strenuous efforts to record how the items in their collections were acquired.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] These records are often of use in helping to establish a chain of provenance.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Scientific research is generally held to be of good provenance when it is documented in detail sufficient to allow reproducibility.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Scientific workflow systems assist scientists and programmers with tracking their data through all transformations, analyses, and interpretations.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Data sets are reliable when the processes used to create them are reproducible and analyzable for defects.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Security researchers are interested in data provenance because it can analyze suspicious data and make large opaque systems transparent.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Current initiatives to effectively manage, share, and reuse ecological data are indicative of the increasing importance of data provenance.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Examples of these initiatives are National Science Foundation Datanet projects, DataONE and Data Conservancy, as well as the U.S.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Some international academic consortia, such as the Research Data Alliance, have specific groups to tackle issues of provenance.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In that case it is the Research Data Provenance Interest Group.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Within computer science, informatics uses the term "provenance" to mean the lineage of data, as per data provenance, with research in the last decade extending the conceptual model of causality and relation to include processes that act on data and agents that are responsible for those processes.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] See, for example, the proceedings of the International Provenance Annotation Workshop (IPAW) and Theory and Practice of Provenance (TaPP).
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Interoperability is a design goal of most recent computer science provenance theories and models, for example the Open Provenance Model (OPM) 2008 generation workshop aimed at "establishing inter-operability of systems" through information exchange agreements.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Data models and serialisation formats for delivering provenance information typically reuse existing metadata models where possible to enable this.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Both the OPM Vocabulary and the PROV Ontology make extensive use of metadata models such as Dublin Core and Semantic Web technologies such as the Web Ontology Language (OWL).
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Current practice is to rely on the W3C PROV data model, OPM's successor.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] There are several maintained and open-source provenance capture implementation at the operating system level such as CamFlow, Progger for Linux and MS Windows, and SPADE for Linux, MS Windows, and MacOS.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Operating system level provenance have gained interest in the security community notably to develop novel intrusion detection techniques.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Other implementations exist for specific programming and scripting languages, such as RDataTracker for R, and NoWorkflow for Python.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In the geologic use of the term, provenance instead refers to the origin or source area of particles within a rock, most commonly in sedimentary rocks.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] It does not refer to the circumstances of the collection of the rock.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The provenance of sandstone, in particular, can be evaluated by determining the proportion of quartz, feldspar, and lithic fragments (see diagram).
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Seed provenance refers to the geographic location of a parent plant, from which seeds were collected.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In the context of ecological restoration, seed provenancing refers to a seed-sourcing strategy that focuses on the geographic location of seed sources, as each provenance can describe the genetic material from that location.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Local provenancing is a position maintained by ecologists that suggests that only seeds of local provenance should be planted in a particular area.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] However, this view depends on the adaptationist program – a view that populations are universally locally adapted.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] It is maintained that local seed is best adapted to local conditions, and that outbreeding depression will be avoided.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Background population maladaptation can be driven by natural processes.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Human actions of habitat fragmentation drive maladaptation up and adaptive potential down.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Population fragments are unlikely to divergence by natural selection since fragmentation (< 500 years).
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] This leads to a low risk of outbreeding depression.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Provenance trials, where material of different provenances are planted in a single place or at different locations spanning a range of environmental conditions, is a way to reveal genetic variation among provenances.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] It also contributes to an understanding of how different provenances respond to various climatic and environmental conditions and can as such contribute with knowledge on how to strategically select provenances for climate change adaptation.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The term *provenance* is used when ascertaining the source of goods such as computer hardware to assess if they are genuine or counterfeit.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Chain of custody is an equivalent term used in law, especially for evidence in criminal or commercial cases.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Software provenance encompasses the origin of software and its licensing terms.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] For example, when incorporating a free, open source or proprietary software component in an application, one may wish to understand its provenance to ensure that licensing requirements are fulfilled and that other software characteristics can be understood.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Data provenance covers the provenance of computerized data.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] There are two main aspects of data provenance: ownership of the data and data usage.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Ownership will tell the user who is responsible for the source of the data, ideally including information on the originator of the data.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Data usage gives details regarding how the data has been used and modified and often includes information on how to cite the data source or sources.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Data provenance is of particular concern with electronic data, as data sets are often modified and copied without proper citation or acknowledgement of the originating data set.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Databases make it easy to select specific information from data sets and merge this data with other data sources without any documentation of how the data was obtained or how it was modified from the original data set or sets.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] The automated analysis of data provenance graphs has been described as a mean to verify compliance with regulations regarding data usage such as introduced by the EU GDPR.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Secure Provenance refers to providing integrity and confidentiality guarantees to provenance information.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] In other words, secure provenance means to ensure that history cannot be rewritten, and users can specify who else can look into their actions on the object.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] A simple method of ensuring data provenance in computing is to mark a file as read only.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] This allows the user to view the contents of the file, but not edit or otherwise modify it.
[src:slsa-framework/provenance] Read only can also in some cases prevent the user from accidentally or intentionally deleting the file.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] Reproducible builds can act as part of a chain of trust; the source code can be signed, and deterministic compilation can prove that the binary was compiled from trusted source code.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] Verified reproducible builds provide a strong countermeasure against attacks where binaries do not match their source code, e.g., because an attacker has inserted malicious code into a binary.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] This is a relevant attack; attackers sometimes attack binaries but not the source code, e.g., because they can only change the distributed binary or to evade detection since it is the source code that developers normally review and modify.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] In a survey of 17 experts, reproducible builds had a very high utility rating from 58.8% participants, but also a high-cost rating from 70.6%.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] Various efforts are being made to modify software development tools to reduce these costs.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] For the compilation process to be deterministic, the input to the compiler must be the same, regardless of the build environment used.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] This typically involves normalizing variables that may change, such as order of input files, timestamps, locales, and paths.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] Additionally, the compilers must not introduce non-determinism themselves.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] This sometimes happens when using hash tables with a random hash seed value.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] It can also happen when using the address of variables because that varies from address space layout randomization (ASLR).
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] Build systems, such as Bazel, GNU Guix, and Gitian, can be used to automate deterministic build processes.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] The GNU Project used reproducible builds in the early 1990s.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] Changelogs from 1992 indicate the ongoing effort.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] One of the older projects to promote reproducible builds is the Bitcoin project with Gitian, and later, GNU Guix.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] In 2013, the Tor (anonymity network) project started using Gitian for their reproducible builds.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] Starting in 2011, a reproducible Java build system was developed for the decentralized peer-to-peer FOSS project DirectDemocracyP2P.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] The concepts of the system's application to automated updates recommendation support was first presented in April 2013 at Decentralized Coordination.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] A treatise focusing on the implementation details of the reproducible Java compilation tool itself was published in 2015.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] In July 2013, the Debian project started implementing reproducible builds across its entire package archive.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] By July 2017, more than 90% of the packages in the repository were proven to build reproducibly.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] In November 2018, the Reproducible Builds project joined the Software Freedom Conservancy.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] F-Droid uses reproducible builds to provide a guarantee that distributed APKs use the claimed free source code.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] The Tails portable operating system uses reproducible builds and explains to others how to verify their distribution.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] NixOS claims 100% build reproducibility as of June 2021 for their minimal ISO releases.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] As of May 2020, Arch Linux is working on making all official packages reproducible.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] As of March 2025, Debian live images for Bookworm are reproducible.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] The FreeBSD operating system builds reproducibly and without root access since October 2025.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] According to the Reproducible Builds project, timestamps are "the biggest source of reproducibility issues.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] In some cases other changes must be made to make a build process reproducible.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] For example, some data structures do not guarantee a stable order in each execution.
[src:slsa-framework/reproducible-builds] A typical solution is to modify the build process to specify a sorted output from those structures.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] This page covers the detailed technical requirements for producing artifacts at each SLSA level.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] The intended audience is platform implementers and security engineers.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] For an informative description of the levels intended for all audiences, see Levels.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] To better understand the reasoning behind the requirements, see Threats and mitigations.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] The key words “MUST”, “MUST NOT”, “REQUIRED”, “SHALL”, “SHALL NOT”, “SHOULD”, “SHOULD NOT”, “RECOMMENDED”, “MAY”, and “OPTIONAL” in this document are to be interpreted as described in RFC 2119.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] In order to produce artifacts with a specific build level, responsibility is split between the Producer and Build platform.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] The build platform MUST strengthen the security controls in order to achieve a specific level while the producer MUST choose and adopt a build platform capable of achieving a desired build level, implementing any controls as specified by the chosen platform.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] While the exact definition of what constitutes a secure platform is beyond the scope of this specification, all implementations MUST use industry security best practices to be conformant to this specification.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] This includes, but is not limited to, using proper access controls, securing communications, implementing proper management of cryptographic secrets, doing frequent updates, and promptly fixing known vulnerabilities.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] Various relevant standards and guides can be consulted for that matter such as the CIS Critical Security Controls.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] A package’s *producer* is the organization that owns and releases the software.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] It might be an open-source project, a company, a team within a company, or even an individual.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] NOTE: There were more requirements for producers in the initial draft version (v0.1) which impacted how a package can be built.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] These were removed in the v1.0 specification and will be reassessed and re-added as indicated in the future directions.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] The producer MUST select a build platform that is capable of reaching their desired SLSA Build Level.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] For example, if a producer wishes to produce a Build Level 3 artifact, they MUST choose a builder capable of producing Build Level 3 provenance.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] The producer MUST build their artifact in a consistent manner such that verifiers can form expectations about the build process.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] In some implementations, the producer MAY provide explicit metadata to a verifier about their build process.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] In others, the verifier will form their expectations implicitly (e.g. trust on first use).
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] If a producer wishes to distribute their artifact through a package ecosystem that requires explicit metadata about the build process in the form of a configuration file, the producer MUST complete the configuration file and keep it up to date.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] This metadata might include information related to the artifact’s source repository and build parameters.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] The producer MUST distribute provenance to artifact consumers.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] The producer MAY delegate this responsibility to the package ecosystem, provided that the package ecosystem is capable of distributing provenance.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] A package’s *build platform* is the infrastructure used to transform the software from source to package.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] This includes the transitive closure of all hardware, software, persons, and organizations that can influence the build.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] A build platform is often a hosted, multi-tenant build service, but it could be a system of multiple independent rebuilders, a special-purpose build platform used by a single software project, or even an individual’s workstation.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] Ideally, one build platform is used by many different software packages so that consumers can minimize the number of trusted platforms.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] The build platform is responsible for providing two things: provenance generation and isolation between builds.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] The Build level describes the degree to which each of these properties is met.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] The build platform is responsible for generating provenance describing how the package was produced.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] The build platform is responsible for isolating between builds, even within the same tenant project.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] In other words, how strong of a guarantee do we have that the build really executed correctly, without external influence?
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] The SLSA Build level describes the minimum bar for isolation strength.
[src:slsa-framework/requirements] For more information on assessing a build platform’s isolation strength, see Verifying build platforms.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] A **software build** is the process of converting source code files into standalone software artifact(s) that can be run on a computer, or the result of doing so.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] In include functions such as version control, code quality analysis, compilation, and linking.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] In software production, builds optimize software for performance and distribution, packaging into formats such as '.*exe'; '.deb'; '.apk'*.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] The build process often employs specialized tools such as CMake, Make, or Gradle, and integrates with automation systems including Jenkins or GitHub Actions.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] Despite advancements, challenges such as dependency conflicts, platform compatibility, and long compile times, remain problems.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] In software development, building software is an end-to-end process that involves many distinct functions.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] Some of these functions are described below.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] The version control function carries out activities such as workspace creation and updating, baselining and reporting.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] It creates an environment for the build process to run in and captures metadata about the inputs and output of the build process to ensure repeatability and reliability.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] Tools such as Git, AccuRev or StarTeam help with these tasks by offering tools to tag specific points in history as being important, and more.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] Also known as static program analysis/static code analysis this function is responsible for checking that developers have adhered to the seven axes of code quality: comments, unit tests, duplication, complexity, coding rules, potential bugs and architecture & design.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] Ensuring a project has high-quality code results in fewer bugs and influences nonfunctional requirements such as maintainability, extensibility and readability; which have a direct impact on the ROI for a business.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] This is only a small feature of managing the build process.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] The compilation function turns source files into directly executable or intermediate objects.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] Not every project will require this function.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] While for simple programs the process consists of a single file being compiled, for complex software the source code may consist of many files and may be combined in different ways to produce many different versions.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] A linker or link editor is a computer program that combines intermediate software build files such as object and library files into a single executable file such as a program or library.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] A linker is often part of a toolchain that includes a compiler and/or assembler that generates intermediate files that the linker processes.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] The linker may be integrated with other toolchain tools such that the user does not interact with the linker directly.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] A simpler version that writes its output directly to memory is called the *loader*, though loading is typically considered a separate process.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] The process of building a computer program is usually managed by a build tool, a program that coordinates and controls other programs.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] Examples of such a program are make, Gradle, Ant, Maven, Rake, SCons and Phing.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] The build utility typically needs to compile the various files, in the correct order.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] If the source code in a particular file has not changed then it may not need to be recompiled ("may not" rather than "need not" because it may itself depend on other files that have changed).
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] Sophisticated build utilities and linkers attempt to refrain from recompiling code that does not need it, to shorten the time required to complete the build.
[src:slsa-framework/software-build] A more complex process may involve other programs producing code or data as part of the build process and software.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] A **supply chain attack** is a cyber-attack that seeks to damage an organization by targeting less secure elements in the supply chain.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain attack can occur in any industry, from the financial sector, oil industry, to a government sector.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain attack can happen in software or hardware.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Cybercriminals typically tamper with the manufacturing or distribution of a product by installing malware or hardware-based spying components.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Symantec's 2019 Internet Security Threat Report states that supply chain attacks increased by 78 percent in 2018.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain is a system of activities involved in handling, distributing, manufacturing, and processing goods in order to move resources from a vendor into the hands of the final consumer.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain is a complex network of interconnected players governed by supply and demand.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Alternatively, the term can be used to describe attacks exploiting the software supply chain, in which an apparently low-level or unimportant software component used by other software can be used to inject malicious code into the larger software that depends on the component.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In a more general sense, a supply chain attack may not necessarily involve electronics.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In 2010 when burglars gained access to the pharmaceutical giant Eli Lilly's supply warehouse, by drilling a hole in the roof and loading $80 million worth of prescription drugs into a truck, they could also have been said to carry out a supply chain attack.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] However, this article will discuss cyber attacks on physical supply networks that rely on technology; hence, a supply chain attack is a method used by cyber-criminals.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Generally, supply chain attacks on information systems begin with an advanced persistent threat (APT) that determines a member of the supply network with the weakest cyber security in order to affect the target organization.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Hackers don't usually directly target a larger entity, such as the United States Government, but instead target the entity's software.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The third-party software is often less protected, leading to an easier target.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] According to an investigation produced by Verizon Enterprise, 92% of the cyber security incidents analyzed in their survey occurred among small firms.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain networks are considered to be particularly vulnerable due to their multiple interconnected components.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] APTs can often gain access to sensitive information by physically tampering with the production of the product.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Poorly managed supply chain management systems can become significant hazards for cyber attacks, which can lead to a loss of sensitive customer information, disruption of the manufacturing process, and could damage a company's reputation.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Wired reported a connecting thread in recent software supply chain attacks, as of 3 May 2019.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] These have been surmised to have spread from infected, pirated, popular compilers posted on pirate websites.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] That is, corrupted versions of Apple's Xcode and Microsoft Visual Studio.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] At the end of 2013, Target, a US retailer, was hit by one of the largest data breaches in the history of the retail industry.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Between 27 November and 15 December 2013, Target's American brick-and-mortar stores experienced a data hack.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Around 40 million customers' credit and debit cards became susceptible to fraud after malware was introduced into the POS system in over 1,800 stores.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The data breach of Target's customer information saw a direct impact on the company's profit, which fell 46 percent in the fourth quarter of 2013.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Six months prior the company began installing a $1.6 million cyber security system.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Target had a team of security specialists to monitor its computers constantly.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Nonetheless, the supply chain attack circumvented these security measures.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] It is believed that cyber criminals infiltrated a third party supplier to gain access to Target's main data network.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Although not officially confirmed, investigation officials suspect that the hackers first broke into Target's network on 15 November 2013 using passcode credentials stolen from Fazio Mechanical Services, a Pennsylvania-based provider of HVAC systems.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Ninety lawsuits have been filed against Target by customers for carelessness and compensatory damages.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Target spent around $61 million responding to the breach, according to its fourth-quarter report to investors.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet is a computer worm that is widely believed to be a joint U.S.-Israeli cyber operation, though neither government has officially confirmed involvement.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The worm specifically targets industrial control systems, particularly those that automate electromechanical processes, such as factory machinery and nuclear enrichment equipment.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet was designed to manipulate programmable logic controllers (PLCs), disrupting industrial equipment by issuing unauthorized commands while simultaneously feeding falsified operations data to monitoring systems to conceal its activity.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet is widely believed to have been developed to disrupt Iran's enriched uranium programs.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Kevin Hogan, Senior Director of Security Response at Symantec, stated that most infections occurred in Iran.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Analysts suggest that its primary target was the Natanz uranium enrichment facility.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet was initially introduced into Iran's Natanz facility via infected USB flash drives, requiring physical access to the target network.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] According to reports, engineers or maintenance workers, either knowingly or unknowingly, facilitated its entry into the plant.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Once inside, the worm spread autonomously, exploiting multiple zero-day vulnerabilities in Windows systems to propagate across networked machines running Siemens industrial control software.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In recent years malware known as Suceful, Plotus, Tyupkin and GreenDispenser have affected automated teller machines globally, especially in Russia and Ukraine.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] GreenDispenser specifically gives attackers the ability to walk up to an infected ATM system and remove its cash vault.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] When installed, GreenDispenser may display an 'out of service' message on the ATM, but attackers with the right access credentials can drain the ATM's cash vault and remove the malware from the system using an untraceable delete process.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The other types of malware usually behave in a similar fashion, capturing magnetic stripe data from the machine's memory storage and instructing the machines to withdraw cash.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The attacks require a person with insider access, such as an ATM technician or anyone else with a key to the machine, to place the malware on the ATM.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The Tyupkin malware active in March 2014 on more than 50 ATMs at banking institutions in Eastern Europe, is believed to have also spread at the time to the U.S., India, and China.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The malware affects ATMs from major manufacturers running Microsoft Windows 32-bit operating systems.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The malware displays information on how much money is available in every machine and allows an attacker to withdraw 40 notes from the selected cassette of each ATM.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In June 2017, the financial software M.E.Doc, widely used in Ukraine, was identified by security researchers as a likely initial vector for the spread of the NotPetya malware.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Security researchers, including those from Microsoft, indicated that NotPetya infections may have originated from a compromised update issued through M.E.Doc.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Some analysts described this as a supply chain attack, though the exact method of compromise was not definitively identified.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The software's developers denied the claim but later deleted their statement and stated that they were cooperating with investigators.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] NotPetya was initially identified as ransomware because it encrypted hard drives and displayed a ransom demand in bitcoin.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] However, the email account used to provide decryption keys was shut down, leaving victims without a way to recover their files.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Unlike WannaCry, NotPetya had no built-in kill switch, making it harder to stop.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The attack affected multiple industries in Ukraine, including banks, an airport, the Kyiv Metro, pharmaceutical companies, and Chernobyl's radiation detection systems.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] It also spread globally, impacting organizations in Russia, the United Kingdom, India, and the United States.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] NotPetya spread using EternalBlue, a vulnerability originally developed by the U.S.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] National Security Agency (NSA) and later leaked.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] EternalBlue had previously been used in the WannaCry cyberattack in May 2017.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] This exploit enabled NotPetya to spread through the Windows Server Message Block (SMB) protocol.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The malware also used PsExec and the Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI) to spread within networks.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Due to these exploits, once a device on a network was infected, the malware could rapidly spread to other connected systems.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Ukrainian police stated that M.E.Doc employees could face criminal liability for negligence, citing repeated warnings from antivirus firms about security vulnerabilities in the company's cybersecurity infrastructure.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The head of Ukraine's CyberPolice, Colonel Serhiy Demydiuk, alleged that M.E.Doc had been repeatedly warned by security firms about weaknesses in its systems but failed to act, stating, "They knew about it." Authorities later reported that M.E.Doc cooperated with investigators.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] From August 21 until September 5, 2018 British Airways was under attack.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The British Airways website payment section contained a code that harvested customer payment data.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The injected code was written specifically to route credit card information to a domain baways.com, which could erroneously be thought to belong to British Airways.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Magecart is the entity believed to be behind the attack.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Magecart is a name attributed to multiple hacker groups that use skimming practices in order to steal customer information through online payment processes.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Approximately 380,000 customers had their personal and financial data compromised as a result of the attack.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] British Airways later reported in October, 2018 that an additional 185,000 customers may have had their personal information stolen as well.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The 2020 SolarWinds cyberattack was linked to a supply chain compromise targeting the IT infrastructure company SolarWinds, which provided software used by multiple U.S. federal institutions, including networks within the National Nuclear Security Administration (NNSA).
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Russian hackers compromised Orion, a widely used network management software developed by SolarWinds, by injecting malicious code into software updates.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] This allowed them to gain unauthorized access to numerous organizations, including multiple U.S. government agencies that relied on Orion for IT monitoring and management.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Department of Homeland Security issued Emergency Directive 21-01, "*Mitigate SolarWinds Orion Code Compromise",* requiring affected federal agencies to disconnect compromised Windows host OS instances from their enterprise domain and rebuild those hosts using trusted sources.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] These compromised systems had been running SolarWinds Orion.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In December 2020, FireEye identified a cyber breach involving the SolarWinds Orion software, which had been compromised prior to its discovery.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Microsoft was among the organizations affected, detecting and removing malicious files linked to the breach.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Microsoft has since collaborated with FireEye as part of an ongoing investigation into the incident.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The cyberattack targeted supply chain software used across various industries, including government, consulting, technology, telecommunications, and extractive sectors in North America, Europe, Asia and the Middle East.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] None of the Microsoft repositories contained production credentials.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The repositories were secured in December, and those attacks ceased in January.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] However, in March 2021 more than 20,000 US organizations were compromised through a back door that was installed via flaws in Exchange Server.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The affected organizations use self-hosted e-mail (on-site rather than cloud-based) such as credit unions, town governments, and small businesses.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The flaws were patched on 2 March 2021, but by 5 March 2021 only 10% of the compromised organizations had implemented the patch; the back door remains open.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The US officials are attempting to notify the affected organizations which are smaller than the organizations that were affected in December 2020.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Microsoft has updated its Indicators of Compromise tool and has released emergency mitigation measures for its Exchange Server flaws.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The attacks on SolarWinds and Microsoft software are currently thought to be independent, as of March 2021.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The Indicators of Compromise tool allows customers to scan their Exchange Server log files for compromise.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] At least 10 attacking groups are using the Exchange Server flaws.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Web shells can remain on a patched server; this still allows cyberattacks based on the affected servers.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] As of 12 March 2021 exploit attempts are doubling every few hours, according to Check Point Research, some in the name of security researchers themselves.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] By 14 April 2021 the FBI had completed a covert cyber operation to remove the web shells from afflicted servers and was informing the servers' owners of what had been done.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In May 2021 Microsoft identified 3000 malicious emails to 150 organizations in 24 countries, that were launched by a group that Microsoft has denoted 'Nobelium'.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Many of those emails were blocked before delivery.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] 'Nobelium' gained access to a Constant Contact "email marketing account used by the US Agency for International Development (USAID)".
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Security researchers assert that 'Nobelium' crafts spear-phishing email messages which get clicked on by unsuspecting users; the links then direct installation of malicious 'Nobelium' code to infect the users' systems, making them subject to ransom, espionage, disinformation, etc.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The US government has identified 'Nobelium' as stemming from Russia's Federal Security Service.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] By July 2021 the US government is expected to name the initiator of the Exchange Server attacks: "China's Ministry of State Security has been using criminal contract hackers".
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In September 2021 the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) enforcement staff have requested that any companies which have downloaded any compromised SolarWinds updates, voluntarily turn over data to the SEC if they have installed the compromised updates on their servers.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In July 2022 SessionManager, a malicious module hosted by IIS (installed by default on Exchange Servers), was discovered to have infected Exchange Servers since March 2021; SessionManager searches memory for passwords, and downloads new modules, to hijack the server.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Mandiant, a security firm, has shown that nation-state-sponsored groups, once they have gained access to corporate clouds, can now exploit Security assertion markup language (SAML), to gain federated authentication to Active Directory and similar services, at will.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Once the attackers gain access, they are able to infiltrate any information or assets belonging to the organization.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] This is because this technique allows attackers to pose as any member of the targeted organization.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] These attacks are progressively becoming more desirable to malicious actors as companies and agencies continue to move assets to cloud services.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In 2020, SolarWinds was subject to what is described as the first documented Golden SAML attack, often referred to as "Solorigate".
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] A malicious actor infected the source code of a software update with a backdoor code made to look legitimate.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Customers began installing the faulty update to their systems, ultimately affecting over 18,000 individuals globally.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The attack affected a number of United States government agencies and private sector agencies as well.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In May 2021, a ransomware attack on Colonial Pipeline forced a temporary shutdown of a major fuel distribution network, disrupting the supply of gasoline, diesel, and jet fuel to the U.S.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The Biden administration invoked emergency powers to prevent shortages, while experts described the incident as the worst-ever cyberattack on U.S. infrastructure.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The attack, attributed to the Russian-linked cybercriminal group DarkSide, raised concerns about vulnerabilities in critical energy systems, as fuel traders sought alternative supply routes and fears of price spikes emerged.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] On June 16, 2021, President Biden stated to President Putin that cyberattacks on 16 critical infrastructure sectors were off-limits and said that the U.S. would respond to future cyber threats.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The 16 critical infrastructure sectors, as designated by the U.S.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA), include energy, food and agriculture, emergency services, healthcare, and other essential industries such as financial services, communications, and transportation systems.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] On 2 July 2021, about 60 managed service providers (MSPs) and their customers became victims of a ransomware attack perpetrated by the REvil group, causing downtime for over 1,000 companies.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] REvil carried out the attack by exploiting a vulnerability in VSA (Virtual System Administrator), a remote monitoring and management software package developed by Kaseya.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] This was a form of supply chain attack on a software supply chain.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] REvil demanded about 70 million USD in Bitcoin as a ransom.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] On 23 July 2021, Kaseya announced that it had received a universal decryptor tool from a "trusted third party", and it helped customers restore their data.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Two suspects were identified and one sentenced.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In March 2023, the voice and video chat app 3CX Phone System was thought to have been subject to a supply chain attack due to detection of malicious activity on the software.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The app is used in a wide variety of industries from food to automotive and an attack has the potential to impact hundreds of thousands of users worldwide.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The malware infects the host device through the installation process, acting as a Trojan horse virus spread through both Mac OS and Microsoft installers.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] They employed an infostealer through a malicious payload that connected to a C2 server controlled by the threat actor.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The attack utilized the Gopuram backdoor, originally discovered by the Russian cybersecurity company Kaspersky in 2020.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The use of this backdoor suggested that the attack was executed by the North Korean cybercrime group known as Lazarus due to their use of this same backdoor in a 2020 attack against a South Asian cryptocurrency company.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The Gopuram backdoor has been utilized in other past attacks against cryptocurrency agencies, which Lazarus has been known to target.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In July 2023, Chinese state-sponsored hackers targeted the United States Department of State, hacking several government employees' Microsoft email accounts, which gave them access to classified information.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] They stole information from about 60,000 emails from several Department of State employees.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Department of State officials have stated that the information stolen includes "victims' travel itineraries and diplomatic deliberations".
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] If used in a malicious manner, this information could be used to monitor important government officials and track United States communications that are meant to be confidential.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The Department of State hack occurred due to vulnerabilities in Microsoft Exchange Server, classifying it as a supply-chain attack.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In March 2024, a backdoor in xz/liblzma in XZ Utils was suspected, with malicious code known to be in version 5.6.0 and 5.6.1.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] While the exploit remained dormant unless a specific third-party patch of the SSH server is used, under the right circumstances this interference could potentially enable a malicious actor to break sshd authentication and gain unauthorized access to the entire system remotely.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The list of affected Linux distributions includes Debian unstable, Fedora Rawhide, Kali Linux, and OpenSUSE Tumbleweed.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Most Linux distributions that followed a stable release update model were not affected, since they were carrying older versions of xz.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Arch Linux issued an advisory for users to update immediately, although it also noted that Arch's OpenSSH package does not include the common third-party patch necessary for the backdoor.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] FreeBSD is not affected by this attack, as all supported FreeBSD releases include versions of xz that predate the affected releases and the attack targets Linux's glibc.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] On October 31, 2024, cybersecurity researchers from several security firms such as Phylum, Socket, and Checkmarx detected an attack on users of the open-source Node Package Manager (NPM) library.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Unidentified attackers published more than 287 packages in an attempt to trick users of the platform into downloading malicious code.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The attack used a technique called typosquatting, which copies the names of legitimate packages closely, tricking unsuspecting developers into accidentally downloading the wrong one.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] For the package Fetch-mock-jest, the attacker rearranged the order of the words and misspelled the word fetch creating the name "jest-fet-mock".
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Based on the kind of packages mimicked, researchers believe this attack widely targeted software developers using NPM.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Packages targeted are mostly mock HTTP requests and cryptocurrency-related, including Puppeteer, Bignum.js, and Fetch-mock-jest, which are mainly used in development environments.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Phylum researchers noted that these typosquatted packages seemed normal at first glance, but upon closer inspection, they contained obfuscated code that could not be understood.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] After de-obfuscating the code, researchers found that after the malicious package is mistakenly downloaded it automatically runs a script that interacts with an Ethereum smart contract to retrieve the IP addresses of the command and control server (C2) used by the attackers.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The script then identifies the operating system used by the victim machine and downloads compatible malware from the IP address it received from the contract.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] This malware maintains persistent communication with the attacker's C2 server, periodically leaking the user's system information such as the operating system version, GPU, CPU, the amount of memory on the machine, and username.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Checkmarkx researcher Yahud Gelb explains that if researchers attempt to take down a C2 server at a specific IP address, the attacker can just update the Ethereum contract so that it returns a different address.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] When describing the mechanism behind the contract he wrote: "Think of a smart contract on the Ethereum blockchain as a public bulletin board – anyone can read what's posted, but only the owner has the ability to update it".
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] This complicates the issue because the malware can always query the smart contract to update the stored address of the C2 server in case the current one has been taken down by authorities.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Researchers worried that several companies' software development supply chains can be put at risk when attackers typosquat them.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] They elaborate that the untraceable nature of the attack combined with its precisely engineered methods of persistence only adds to the looming threat.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Furthermore, company employees usually have elevated system privileges and access to CI/CD pipelines when using development environments, further endangering the company's and their customer's data.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] They warned that developers who use npm packages like the ones above at any stage of the software development lifecycle must take caution and implement robust dependency scanning before performing any installations.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] There is little to no information on the attackers' identity or their motive.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] However, researchers did find error messages written in Russian within the de-obfuscated code of the malicious packages, but they speculate that this could be a misdirect set up by the real culprits trying to throw off any suspicions.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In 2025, the popular text editor Notepad++ was subjected to a sophisticated supply chain attack when threat actors compromised the application's update infrastructure at the hosting provider level.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The attack, which began in June 2025 and continued through December 2025, involved the interception and redirection of update traffic from the official notepad-plus-plus.org domain to attacker-controlled servers.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] According to the Notepad++ maintainer, the shared hosting server was fully compromised until September 2, 2025, after which attackers maintained access to internal service credentials until December 2, 2025, allowing them to continue redirecting update traffic.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Kaspersky researchers identified three primary execution chains used between July and October 2025, with attackers constantly changing command-and-control server addresses, downloaders, and final payloads to evade detection.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Security firm Rapid7 attributed the campaign to the Lotus Blossom group (also known as Violet Typhoon or APT31), linking the attacks to infrastructure and tactics previously observed in campaigns targeting cryptocurrency companies and critical infrastructure.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] On January 20, 2026, the eScan antivirus software, developed by Indian cybersecurity firm MicroWorld Technologies, was compromised in a supply chain attack when threat actors breached one of the company's regional update servers and deployed malware to customer systems.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The incident lasted approximately one hour before being detected by security researchers at Morphisec and Kaspersky.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The attack primarily affected users in South Asia, including India, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, and the Philippines.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Attackers replaced the legitimate Reload.exe component of eScan with a malicious executable that disabled future antivirus updates and downloaded additional payloads from command-and-control servers.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] This marked the second breach of eScan's infrastructure, following a 2024 incident where North Korean state-sponsored group Kimsuky exploited the same update mechanism to deploy backdoors and cryptocurrency miners.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] No attribution has been made for the 2026 attack.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] On 12 May 2021, Executive Order 14028 (the EO), *Improving the nation's cybersecurity*, tasked NIST as well as other US government agencies with enhancing the cybersecurity of the United States.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The Comprehensive National Cybersecurity Initiative and the Cyberspace Policy Review passed by the Bush and Obama administrations respectively, direct U.S. federal funding for development of multi-pronged approaches for global supply chain risk management.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] According to Adrian Davis of the Technology Innovation Management Review, securing organizations from supply chain attacks begins with building cyber-resilient systems.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain resilience is, according to supply chain risk management expert Donal Walters, "the ability of the supply chain to cope with unexpected disturbances" and one of its characteristics is a company-wide recognition of where the supply chain is most susceptible to infiltration.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain management plays a crucial role in creating effective supply chain resilience.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In March 2015, under the Conservative and Liberal democratic government coalition, the UK Department for Business outlined new efforts to protect SMEs from cyber attacks, which included measures to improve supply chain resilience.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The UK government has produced the Cyber Essentials Scheme, which trains firms for good practices to protect their supply chain and overall cyber security.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] In 2025, a study by the Austrian Chamber of Commerce (WKO) and AV-Comparatives identified what cybersecurity firms should do to assure their customers about supply chain security.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] This includes disclosing a software bill of materials, maintaining transparent data storage practices, providing detailed incident reports, and offering facilities where customers can inspect source codes and updates for the cybersecurity product.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Only 3 of the 14 vendors examined provided such assurances.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain attacks have prompted regulatory bodies to address third-party risk management requirements.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] The Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA) issued Binding Operational Directive 22-01, requiring federal agencies to remediate known exploited vulnerabilities within specified timeframes.
[src:slsa-framework/supply-chain-attack] NIST Special Publication 800-161 *Cybersecurity Supply Chain Risk Management Practices* provides a framework for organizations to identify, assess, and mitigate supply chain risks throughout the system development life cycle.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] SLSA is organized into a series of levels that provide increasing supply chain security guarantees.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] This gives you confidence that software hasn’t been tampered with and can be securely traced back to its source.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] This page is a descriptive overview of the SLSA levels and tracks, describing their intent.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] For the prescriptive requirements for each level, see Requirements.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] For a general overview of SLSA, see About SLSA.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] Each track has its own set of levels that measure a particular aspect of supply chain security.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] The purpose of tracks is to recognize progress made in one aspect of security without blocking on an unrelated aspect.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] Tracks also allow the SLSA spec to evolve: we can add more tracks without invalidating previous levels.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] The SLSA build track describes increasing levels of trustworthiness and completeness in a package artifact’s *provenance*.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] Provenance describes what entity built the artifact, what process they used, and what the inputs were.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] The lowest level only requires the provenance to exist, while higher levels provide increasing protection against tampering of the build, the provenance, or the artifact.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] The primary purpose of the build track is to enable verification that the artifact was built as expected.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] Consumers have some way of knowing what the expected provenance should look like for a given package and then compare each package artifact’s actual provenance to those expectations.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] Doing so prevents several classes of supply chain threats.
[src:slsa-framework/v1-0-levels] Guidelines for implementers can be found in the requirements.
